and the disproportionate political influence of the wealthy, assessment of proposed new strategies for increasing political knowledge, and up-to-date survey data on political ignorance during recent elections. Ilya Somin mines the depths of the current state of ignorance in America and reveals it as a major problem for democracy. He weighs various options for solving this problem, provocatively arguing that political ignorance is best mitigated and its effects lessened by decentralizing and limiting government. People make better decisions when they have stronger incentives to acquire relevant information-and to use it wisely.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aDemocracyzUnited States. 0aIgnorance (Theory of knowledge) - Political aspects - United States. 0aIgnorance (Theory of knowledge)xPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aVotingzUnited States. 4acountermajoritarian difficulty. 4ademocracy. 4aelections. 4afederalism. 4afoot voting. 4ajudicial review. 4apolitical ignorance. 4arational choice. 4avoting with your feet. 4avoting. 7aLAW / Constitutional.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479935540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804799355423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804799355.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles